05850nam a22008055i 9780520972681DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019023216  a97805209726817 a10.1525/97805209726812doi  a(DE-B1597)563080  a(OCoLC)1110144152  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHQ766.5.U5 4aHQ766.5.U5bW534 2020 7aSOC0390002bisacsh04a261.8/362231 aWilde, Melissa J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBirth Control Battles :bHow Race and Class Divided American Religion /cMelissa J. Wilde. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. From Abolition to Eugenics -- t1. American Religious Activism in the Twentieth Century -- t2. Mobilizing America's Religious Elite in the Service of Eugenics -- tPART II. Liberalization, 1929-1931 -- t3. The Early Liberalizers: "The Church Has a Responsibility for the Improvement of the Human Stock" -- t4. The Supporters: "God Needed the White Anglo-Saxon Race" -- t5. The Critics: "Atlanta Does Not Believe in Race Suicide" -- t6. The Silent Groups: "Let the Christian Get Away from Heredity" -- tPART III. From Legality to the Pill, 1935-1965 -- t7. The Religious Promoters of Contraception: Remaining Focused on Other People's Fertility -- t8. The Forgotten Half: America's Reluctant Contraceptive Converts -- tConclusion: A Century Later -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConservative and progressive religious groups fiercely disagree about issues of sex and gender. But how did we get here? Melissa J. Wilde shows how today's modern divisions began in the 1930s in the public battles over birth control and not for the reasons we might expect. By examining thirty of America's most prominent religious groups-from Mormons to Methodists, Southern Baptists to Seventh Day Adventists, and many others-Wilde contends that fights over birth control had little do with sex, women's rights, or privacy.Using a veritable treasure trove of data, including census and archival materials and more than 10,000 articles, statements, and sermons from religious and secular periodicals, Wilde demonstrates that the push to liberalize positions on contraception was tied to complex views of race, immigration, and manifest destiny among America's most prominent religious groups. Taking us from the Depression era, when support for the eugenics movement saw birth control as an act of duty for less desirable groups, to the 1960s, by which time most groups had forgotten the reasons behind their stances on contraception (but not the concerns driving them), Birth Control Battles explains how reproductive politics divided American religion. In doing so, this book shows the enduring importance of race and class for American religion as it rewrites our understanding of what it has meant to be progressive or conservative in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aBirth controlxReligious aspectsxHistory. 0aBirth controlzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEugenicszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRace relationsxReligious aspects. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  abirth control as act of duty.  abook about birth control.  afights over birth control.  ahistory behind birth control.  anineteen sixties.  anineteen thirties.  apublic battles over birth control.  apush to liberalize positions on contraception.  areligion and sociology.  areproductive politics divided american